Introduction

Following the Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act that was mandated in 1993, the FBI launched the National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS) on November 30, 1998. NICS is used by Federal Firearms Licensees (FFL) to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Prior to making a sale, FFL's or other designated agencies use the NICS to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record. The gun data that I will be exploring is provided by the NICS. I will also be exploring 2016 Census data that was retrieved from Census.gov.

Below I will be analyzing and exploring the data to answer these 3 questions:

  • Question 1: What 2016 Census data trends closely with 2016 FBI gun data?
  • Question 2: What type of gun has the most background checks performed?
  • Question 3: What US State performs the most background checks on the gun type answer from question 2?

    Question 3 Answer:¶

  • Pennsylvania has the highest amount of long gun backgound checks compared to all other US States.

    • Conclusions

    After getting a more in-depth look at the 2016 Census data and the FBI gun data, I was able to compare 2016 data from both datasets by using the US States as a key identifier. From this, I found that population size generally follows the same trends as background checks for guns and explosives. Kentucky had the highest amount of background checks which did not directly correlate to the state population. Kentucky performs monthly background checks on every concealed carry permit holder. However, California, Texas, and Florida were among many other states whose 2016 population trends closely followed 2016 FBI background checks for guns and explosives. By exploring the FBI gun data, I found that the highest amount of background checks are performed on long guns. Then from this discovery, I found that Pennsylvania is the state that performs the most background checks for long guns.

    It is important to note that there are some limitations with the data and each background check does not represent the number of firearms sold. Based on varying state laws and purchase scenarios, a one-to-one correlation cannot be made between a firearm background check and a firearm sale. Investigative reporter, Jacob Ryan (2015), found that Kentucky runs a NICS check on each concealed carry license holder, once a month, which makes their numbers stand out in comparison to all other US States. According to the 2016 NICS Operations Report, only 31 US States fully worked with the NICS for all firearm background checks, and 7 US States contact the NICS only for handgun and long gun backgrounds checks. The rest of the background checks are done at a state level. Even with these limitations, the FBIs NICS numbers are still widely accepted as the model for total gun sales in a given time period.
